rComments: A good professor who really cares about what he is teaching. He is always  willing to answer questions. He was never late or unprepared. Loves to have class discussions, and may call on random students. He assigns a lot of reading, and you need to do it to get a good grade. Go to lecture and section and you will learn a lot. Tests aren't bad.

Rasmus really knows what he is talking about and clearly has a strong passion for the subject. He really wants students to learn the material and teaches the class with a very modern perspective. He is extremely helpful during office hours. There is a lot of assigned reading but its worth it. The midterm is easy and there isn't a final. Great class

Great professor, super interesting class. He assigns a lot of reading and a lot of it is pretty important if you want to do well. Attendance is mandatory and he doesn't allow any electronics in class but it's because he genuinely cares and wants people to be there and learn.

Took for TA GE. Class was for the most part easy. Thought material would be on famous philosopher's  ideas (Plato, Aristotle, etc.) but it wasn't. A couple of short essays and take home midterm (no final) which were easy. Only part I disliked was that attendance was mandatory and he picked on people randomly to talk in lecture.
If you take Professor Winther's classes and do the reading and put in effort, you will be rewarded in many ways.

Great professor. Took his intro class to complete a GE, and now I want to take every class he teaches. He's a lot of fun and works hard to make sure all students get engaged in lecture. Little to no homework besides the extensive reading (which I never did). Midterm is take home and final is a group project. Easy & fun class with a great professor!
One of my favorite professors at UCSC, very devoted and engaged with his students, he's neither pedantic nor patronizing, and he makes such an effort to get the class to understand  his points.
Attendance is mandatory ( don't miss 3 classes), but it's totally worth it. Definitely my favorite and most intellectually stimulating class this quarter.

Rasmus is a good teacher. He is very enthusiastic about the subject matter and gets excited when someone brings up a good point or idea. His lectures are interactive and he lets others participate instead of just him talking. I didn't do any of the readings for the sake of time and disinterest, but did well on the midterm and hopefully in the class

In his Intro to Phil class, lectures could be a little unclear (which philosophy is prone to be), but he more than made up for this in office hours. Payed lots of attention to students and got to know the ones who made an effort and/or spoke in class.

great teacher...expect to do a lot of reading and writing.  you can not half ass these classes and expect a good grade/ must put in the work Teacher goes above and beyond the normative style of learning
AMAZING teacher. he actually cares about your education. super smart guy with funky fresh style. hard grader but its college. step up yo game student.

Winther is an amazing professor! He is very knowledgeable and engaging. Challenges students to reach their full potential. I learned so much and still want to pursue the topics. His teaching method is unparraled in the dept, practices a receptive model of education that involves participation on both ends. Voice your concerns-he will hear you out!

Rasmus Winther has been one of the greatest professors I have come across in my undergrad ed. He opened our class with an exert from 'Pedagogy of the Oppressed' and he stuck to it; he allows for the method to become the message, and being in his class means that I have been truly blessed. A++

Couldn't think of a better person to take a senior seminar with. At times Rasmus played the roles of prof, helpful second opinion TA, and even laughing student. His knowledge of the diverse and interesting reading material was great. Classes were something I think everyone looked forward to. I would lump Rasmus into the "great prof" category!

My writing has become so much more clear and concise since I started taking Rasmus' classes. Your writing WILL get better, it WILL get good. He's a hardass, but with just cause. He hands out a lot of reading, but it's all worth it. It doesn't even feel like work (most of the time..). TAKE A RASMUS WINTHER CLASS!

Rasmus is the best!!!!! By far one of the best philosophy teachers at UCSC. He is not an esay A. But you will learn how to write all over again. He is extremely bright, yet humble as wel. He actually cares about his students and puts a ridiculous amount of effort into bettering his student's minds. Take a course with him. You will not regret it.

Winther is one of the hardest working professors that i have ever had. He makes an honest effort to keep the class engaged. He can be a tough grader but he give you the opportunity to correct your mistakes and that's something I've rarely seen in academia.  Most notably, he cares about how you are doing also takes to heart what you think.

Professor Winther is not any easy teacher, but he is very enthusiastic, visibly brilliant, and truly cares about his students and their experience in the class. If you're up for a challenge and ready to have massive amounts of knowledge thrown at you, he's going to be your favorite professor. Also, go to office hours, he's super helpful!

Great teacher. The work load is very demanding but you get a lot out of the class by doing the reading and being active in discussions. He has a lot of insight and knowledge about the topics. I had a wonderful experience in the class. I went in to class apprehensive about the topics and left eager to learn more.

A fantastic professor with high standards who really cares about his students. No philosophy professor at UCSC is nearly as concerned about his students' progress as Professor Winther is. Fair, gives extensive feedback on essays, and very adept at facilitating (interesting) class discussions. Top notch.

American Philosophy (pragmatism) was an extremely rigorous course (at least for me) however, the material IS interesting, more so than any of the other philosophy classes I have taken at UCSC. Rasmus also cares about the students success and is a very useful resource if pursued (office hours!!) I recommend this class to anyone who is interested

Extremely personable and dedicated to his job. He has high standards but is willing to put in the work to help you reach them. Extremely intelligent and inspiring. One of the best teachers I've had and would recommend him to anyone who loves learning and an educational environment with lots of dialogue.

Overall, Rasmus was a great Prof.  He has a pretty relaxed style in class.  This can make for good discussion, but don't let it fool you, his standards are high.  I'd definitely take another course with him, and recommend his class to anyone who's willing to put the effort in.

He was late nearly everyday and asked "random questions" in class that took 20-30 minutes. Often filled with "uuuuhhhhhhh......" by students that hadn't done the reading. Instead of letting someone else jump in, he made the chosen one look stupid and wasted everyone's time.
Excellent!!

Shows a high level of concern for student understanding of material.  He's open to discuss new ideas and concerns, along with spend time to clairy things for the student.  His class is more discussion oriented rather than straight lecturing.

Professor Winther is not afraid to challenge his students.  Some, namely those who don't really go to college to learn, see this as a bad thing, but for those who are looking to strengthen and expand their thinking capabilities, this is a big plus.  This guy is not only really interesting, but also knows his stuff. I will continue taking classes fr

Always fifteen minutes late, then it takes him five to ten minutes to set up. The reading is heavy and he barely touches on it, usually getting off topic. I didnt find him very helpful at all, nor did he make the reading interesting. I wouldnt recommend taking a class taught by him, but if you have to, goodluck!

Prof Winthers lectures are terrible.  He comes to class with a random list of students to call on for questioning on the reading, which goes toward ur grade.  The readings are fairly hard and dull and his disjointed and unorganized lectures don't do a good job of explaining them.  new professor and he takes students questions and opinions 2 serious
